properties.name: Advice
properties.location: Wyperfeld National Park and Patchewollock, Yaapeet, Hopetoun
properties.webBody:
This Advice message is being issued for Wyperfeld National Park and Patchewollock, Yaapeet, Hopetoun.
  • There is a bushfire at Wyperfeld National Park - North South Track that is not yet under control.
  • The bushfire is east of the North South Track and fire crews continue to work on building containment lines. 
  • Today (Sunday 21 December) has been declared a day of Total Fire Ban for the Mallee.
  • This Advice replaces the Watch and Act issued at 8.40 AM. 
There is currently no threat to communities, but you should continue to stay informed and monitor conditions.
What you should do: 
  • Monitor weather conditions and warnings. 
  • Review your fire survival plan. 
  • If you do not have a plan, decide what you will do if the situation changes.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Fire crews will remain in the area.
  • Smoke may be visible from nearby communities and roads. 
This message was issued by Forest Fire Management Victoria.

The next update is expected by 21/12/2025 06:30 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#VicFires)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.webBody:
This Community Information is being issued for Charlton, Yeungroon East, Yeungroon.
  • The grassfire at Resevoir-Parish Rd,Charlton  is now under control,but fire is still burning in a number of trees and stumps. 
  • Emergency services will continue to monitor.
  • The following roads remain closed while being accessed for damage: Charlton-St Arnaud Road, Yeungroon Road and River Road.
  • Check the VicTraffic website for all current road closures https://traffic.transport.vic.gov.au/
  • Smoke may be visible from nearby communities and roads. 
  • This Community Information message replaces the Advice message issued on Saturday 20-12-2025 at 11:49AM.
There is no immediate threat to the community and no action is required.
This message was issued by Country Fire Authority.

Unless the situation changes, this will be the last message issued for this fire

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au.
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226.
  • VicEmergency app.
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfires).
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility:
The following service can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Services on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service for assistance and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.name: Advice
properties.location: Central, Northern Country, North Central, North East and parts of Mallee, West and South Gippsland and East Gippsland, including Bendigo, Shepparton, Seymour, Melbourne, Wangaratta, Swan Hill, Echuca, Wonthaggi and Bacchus Marsh
properties.webBody:
The Bureau of Meteorology has advised that severe thunderstorms are likely across Central, Northern Country, North Central, North East and parts of Mallee, West and South Gippsland and East Gippsland, including Bendigo, Shepparton, Seymour, Melbourne, Wangaratta, Swan Hill, Echuca, Wonthaggi and Bacchus Marsh.
  • Damaging to destructive winds, heavy rain, and large hail are possible.
  • These thunderstorms could be very dangerous. 
  • This Advice replaces the Advice message issued at 1:38pm today. 
Be aware of potential hazards caused by the severe thunderstorms, including floodwater, mud, debris, damaged roads, and fallen trees.
What you should do: 

  • Park your car undercover and away from trees.
  • Check that loose items such as outdoor furniture, umbrellas and trampolines are safely secured before the thunderstorms arrive. 
  • Be aware of hazardous trees - heat, fire or recent storms may make trees unstable and more likely to fall during a storm.
  • If outdoors, move to a safe place indoors. Stay away from trees, gutters, creeks and waterways.
  • Camp away from trees.
  • Stay inside if conditions outside appear dangerous.
  • Drive slowly, obey all road signs and never drive through floodwater.
  • Be aware of hazardous trees - heat, fire or recent storms may make trees unstable and more likely to fall during a storm.
  • Contact family members and neighbours to ensure they are aware of the situation, if safe to do so.
If you are driving:
  • If driving conditions are dangerous, safely pull over away from trees, drains, low lying areas and floodwater.
  • Be aware of road hazards such as mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • For road closure information, check the VicTraffic website, contact your local council or call VicRoads (13 11 70).
Stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.

Call Triple Zero (000) in a life threatening emergency. 
For severe weather related emergency assistance from the SES, phone 132 500.
Impacts in your area:

Potential impacts of the severe thunderstorms may include: 
  • Building damage
  • Fallen power lines
  • Fallen trees and branches
  • Flash flooding
  • Landslides
  • Overflowing drains and gutters
  • Broken windows
  • Damage to vehicles
  • Flooding in properties and homes
  • Dangerous road conditions
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 21/12/2025 05:20 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicstorms)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact the National Relay Service and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.webBody:
This Advice message is being issued for Goomalibee.
  • This Advice message replaces the Advice message issued at 9:52am on Sunday 21 December.
  • The large grassfire that has been burning in Goomalibee, between Tarnook Road and the Broken River, is under control.
  • Emergency services remain working in the area.
  • Only local traffic can travel in this area. See below for more information on road closures.
There is currently no threat to you, but you should stay informed and monitor conditions.
What you should do: 
  • Beware of dangerous tree hazards. Stay well clear of trees and do not walk under them.
  • Keep the roads clear so emergency services can respond.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Small fires may still be burning in this area.
  • Firefighters are patrolling the fire to completely extinguish it.
  • Heavy plant and machinery are operating in the area.
  • Smoke may still be visible from nearby communities and roads.
  • Wandering live stock and damaged fencing in the fire area.
Local road closures are still in place. These are at:
  • intersection of Goomalibee Road and Tarnook Road
  • intersection of Tarnook Road and Burness Road
  • intersection of Terret Rd and Goomalibee Road.
Roads are now being assessed by Benalla Rural City Council for reopening soon.
This message was issued by Country Fire Authority.

The next update is expected by 22/12/2025 12:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfires)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Be aware of potential hazards caused by the severe thunderstorms, including flash flooding, damged buildings, trees down and fallen power lines.

properties.name: Severe Thunderstorm Warning for HEAVY RAINFALL, DAMAGING WINDS and LARGE HAILSTONES
properties.webHeadline:
Severe thunderstorms are likely to produce heavy rainfall that may lead to flash flooding, damaging winds and large hailstones in the warning area over the next several hours. Locations which may be affected include Bendigo, Shepparton, Seymour, Melbourne, Wangaratta, Swan Hill, Echuca, Wonthaggi and Bacchus Marsh.


94 km/h wind gust was recorded at Mount Hotham at 12:55 pm.
93 km/h wind gust was recorded at Falls Creek at 11:16 am.
61.0 mm was recorded at Ovens River (Harrietville) in the 6 hours to 12:45 pm.
42.4 mm was recorded at Halls (Buckland River) in the 2 hours to 10:15 am.
38.4 mm was recorded at Edi Upper in the 1 hour to 9:17 am.
27.4 mm was recorded at Mount Buffalo Chalet in the 30 minutes to 9:01 am.
